  CORE ARGUMENT: Gabriel systematically evaluates three major critiques of EA: (1) the justice critique (EA neglects equality, rights, and urgency); (2) the methodological critique (EA's emphasis on quantification creates bias); and (3) the systemic change critique (EA focuses on symptoms rather than root causes). He argues critics overstate their case but identifies legitimate concerns about EA's tendency to sideline justice considerations and its methodological limitations in domains difficult to quantify.

  RELEVANCE: This comprehensive overview of EA criticisms helps situate the income vs. wealth question within broader debates. The justice critique is particularly relevant: if EA's utilitarian framework inadequately addresses distributive justice, this might extend to questions about fair taxation of wealth vs. income. The methodological critique also applies—income is easier to measure and track than wealth, which may explain EA's practical focus on income despite theoretical neutrality.

  POSITION: Systematic evaluation of EA critiques; finds partial merit in justice and methodological concerns while defending EA's core commitments.
  },
  keywords = {effective-altruism, justice-critique, methodological-critique, systematic-review, High}
}

